training_organizations.name: Alaska OCS – Staff Training
training_organizations.description: The Alaska Office of Children’s Services provides in-house training and staff development for child protection workers, ensuring they are educated in Alaska’s policies, investigative techniques, and culturally appropriate practices for working with Alaska Native families.

training_organizations.name: National Indian Child Welfare Association (NICWA)
training_organizations.description: A national nonprofit that provides training and technical assistance on Alaska Native and American Indian child welfare. NICWA works with Alaska’s state and tribal child protection agencies to support compliance with the Indian Child Welfare Act and to deliver culturally competent services to Native children and families.

policies.TribalFoster: Yes, Tribes within state provide foster care
policies.TribalScreen: Yes, collaboration of Tribes with state/local public welfare agency to conduct screening
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Abuse includes punishment, emotional maltreatment (mental injury)
policies.Def_Subtype_Other: Abandonment includes not meeting parental responsibilities
policies.Tribe_IVE_Specify: Aleut Community of St. Paul Island, Kenaitze Indian Tribe, Maniilaq Association
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes inadequate clothing, inadequate shelter, malnourishment, and medical neglect
policies.EquityStaff_Specify: Dedicated Regional Indian Child Welfare Act Specialists protect and regulate services to Indian children and families and aim to reduce disproportionality by working with Tribes, providing training, and accessing and monitoring ethic disproportionality data
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Reporter_OtherSpecify: Practitioners of the healing arts; Administrative officers of institutions; Members of a child fatality review team or multidisciplinary child protection team; Paid employees of domestic violence, sexual assault programs and crisis intervention programs
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Contact another state's child welfare agency if the child has lived in another state; Coordinate with Tribe if necessary
policies.InvestQual_OtherSpecify: Alaska's Office of Children's Services (OCS) uses competency-based hiring, which does not require specific education or experience, for child protection staff. Competencies include analytical thinking and problem solving, customer service, integrity and honesty, interpersonal skills, oral communication, and writing
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: Any person can be a perpetrator of physical injury or neglect, mental injury, sexual abuse, sexual exploitation, or maltreatment
policies.ScreenerQual_OtherSpecify: Alaska's Office of Children's Services (OCS) uses competency-based hiring, which does not require specific education or experience, for child protection staff. Competencies include analytical thinking and problem solving, customer service, integrity and honesty, interpersonal skills, oral communication, and writing
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: Onboarding with a supervisor; Pre-Standards, Knowledge, and Insight Leading to Success (SKILS) trainings; SKILS trainings; Transfer of learning and intersession trainings; Field-based training with the mentor program
policies.CaseManagerQual_OtherSpecify: Alaska's Office of Children's Services (OCS) uses competency-based hiring, which does not require specific education or experience, for child protection staff. Competencies include analytical thinking and problem solving, customer service, integrity and honesty, interpersonal skills, oral communication, and writing

policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: Onboarding with a supervisor; Pre-Standards, Knowledge, and Insight Leading to Success (SKILS) trainings; SKILS trainings; Transfer of learning and intersession trainings; Field-based training with the mentor program
policies.ReporterTraining_OtherSpecify: A mandated reporter employed by the state or by a school district
policies.InvestReq_MedEvalCases_Specify: If a child discloses sexual abuse during an initial assessment of physical abuse or neglect at a Child Advocacy Center
policies.CaseManagerQual_TrainingSpecify: Onboarding with a supervisor; Pre-Standards, Knowledge, and Insight Leading to Success (SKILS) trainings; SKILS trainings; Transfer of learning and intersession trainings; Field-based training with the mentor program
policies.ExtFosterCare_Reentry_OtherSpec: Youth was placed in out-of-home care by the department immediately prior to being released from state custody, and the person was 1) released to the person's own custody after reaching age 18, 2) at least 16 years of age and emancipated, 3) at least 16 years of age and released to the custody of a parent or guardian because the person refused out-of-home care and has reached the age of 18, or 4) at least 16 years of age and released to the custody of a parent or guardian because the person refused out-of-home care, has not reached the age of 18, and grounds for filing a child in need of aid petition do not exist; If requested by the department, agrees to reasonable terms for resuming state custody that may include matters relating to the person's education, attainment of a job or life skills, or other terms found by the court to be reasonable and in the person's best interest
policies.InvestReq_ReporterCases_Specify: In sexual abuse and serious physical abuse cases in which one of the parents/caretakers is the alleged perpetrator and before visiting the family
policies.ExtFosterCare_Criteria_OtherSpec: If continued state custody is in the child's best interests
policies.InvestReq_PerpInterviewCase_Spec: When the alleged perpetrator lives in the home and it is not a sexual abuse or serious physical abuse case
